"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nFamily Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nCheeseman: - John (Jack) - Michael and Derek:<br />\nAfter the death of Tom Cheeseman, his wife Daisy and their two children Michael and Derek went to live with John (Tom's brother) and Maud (Daisy's sister). The children, at around six years old attended a boarding school called 'Royal Russell' (for families of 'Warehousemen, Clerks and Drapers') and would then stay with John and Maud during school holiday's, sometimes travelling down to Shoreham-by-Sea, West Sussex where they would stay with Gilbert and Edith Richards at <a href=\"media.html?mdx=2\">Tipperary 100 Old Fort Road</a>. (Edith was sister to Henry, Tom, John and Kathleen Cheeseman)\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nHenry (Harry) Leslie Cheeseman:\n</p>\n<p>\nIn the period before the National Health Service and in the event of the death of Henry's father, William Stookley, Henry (the eldest son) would contribute his earnings to the family house hold income.\n</p>\n<p>\nIn August of 1959 Henry, a long established member of the Freemasons, would achieve the honour of <a href=\"media.html?mdx=75\"></a><a href=\"media.html\"><a href=\"media.html?mdx=75\">'London Grand Chapter Rank'.</a></a><a href=\"media.html?mdx=75\"></a> \n</p>\n<p>\nIt is evident from letters received by Laura (Henry's daughter) following Henry's death that he was a well regarded, strait thinking, kind gentleman and even the regional director of <a href=\"media.html?mdx=95\"></a><a href=\"media.html\"><a href=\"media.html?mdx=95\">Midland Bank LTD wrote to Henry upon his retirement</a></a><a href=\"media.html?mdx=95\"></a> and his move to live in Prestbury, wishing to record their pride and satisfaction for having been his banker for almost 60 years.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nKathleen (Kitto) Cheeseman:<br />\nKitto's career started out as a Sales assistance at Dickens &amp; Jones and also Swan &amp; Edgars in Regent Street London and later on she would have her own dress shop in St' Georges Road Wimbledon. After her sister-in-law ( Dulcie Cheeseman, wife to Henry) died, Kitto and Rebecca (mother to Henry and Kitto) moved in to Henry's home and sometime later Kitto would give up her dress shop to help look after Henry's daughter Laura and her mother Rebecca.\n</p>\n<p>\nAll though Laura had lost her mother at an early age, Laura recalls feeling very comfortable in Kitto's company, which is evident in the many photo's of them together.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nFamily Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nCheeseman: - John (Jack) - Michael and Derek:<br />\nAfter the death of Tom Cheeseman, his wife Daisy and their two children Michael and Derek went to live with John (Tom's brother) and Maud (Daisy's sister). The children, at around six years old attended a boarding school called 'Royal Russell' (for families of 'Warehousemen, Clerks and Drapers') and would then stay with John and Maud during school holiday's, sometimes travelling down to Shoreham-by-Sea, West Sussex where they would stay with Gilbert and Edith Richards at <a href=\"media.html?mdx=2\">Tipperary 100 Old Fort Road</a>. (Edith was sister to Henry, Tom, John and Kathleen Cheeseman)\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nForeman at Wall Plate Manufacture<br />\n--<br />\nDied before 27 August 1876 - the year of his sons marriage\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
