"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nGeneral\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nRymans name in the Richards family:\n</p>\n<p>\nIt was thought by Derick Cheeseman that the name Ryman that appeared in the Richards family was due to a connection with the man Henry J Ryman, the founder of Ryman, who opened his first store and the first ever self-service stationery shop in London at Great Portland Street in 1893. However, my research has found little evidence to support this.\n</p>\n<p>\nMy research shows that the name Ryman began to appear during the marriage of William Emmanuel Richards and Thurza Hannah Earl. Between them they had ten children of which six would have the name Ryman in their name with the first appearance going to the third child, Gilbert (born, year 1876).\n</p>\n<p>\nWilliam Emmanuel Richards and Henry John Ryman where born just three years apart but relatively speaking for that period they lived miles apart. William born in 1849 and residing in Oxford and Henry born in 1852 and residing in London.\n</p>\n<p>\nNeither William Richards or Thurza Earl have a parent with the name Ryman.\n</p>\n<p>\nHowever, William Emmanuel Richards occupation as stated in the 1881 Cencus was Printseller Publisher &amp; Carver &amp; Gilder. Could this occupation be a link?\n</p>\n<p>\nAccording to the 1901 census, Gilbert Ryman Richards (born 1876) was residing in St George Hanover Square, London and his occupation was Gunmakers Clerk and then in 1911 and residing at 238 Worple Road Wimbledon, London his occupation was Commercial Traveller Fine Cu Printers And Fancy Goods - could Gilbert be working for Henry J Ryman ? If so, could this be the reason why the Ryman name had been associated with the Richards name ? \n</p>\n<p>\nFor me and for the time being, the reason why the name Ryman came in to being in the Richards family, is unresolved - Do you know something about this?\n</p>\n<p>\nLINKS:<br />\nhttps://www.geni.com/people/Henry-Ryman/6000000039001135655\n</p>\n<p>\nhttps://www.ryman.co.uk/history-of-ryman\n</p>\n<p>\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryman\n</p>\n<p>\n&nbsp;\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
